<div class="span7">
  <div class="well help-topic-content">

    <div id="getting-started">
      <h2>Getting Started</h2>
      <p>
        So you've signed up for the site - great! Now
        The first order of business is to get your roommates on the site - it
        will be difficult to do anything without them. Your roommates will
        first need to join your group - this can be accomplished in two ways:
        <ol>
          <li>Sending an email invitation</li>
          <li>Manually entering the group identifier during signup</li>
        </ol>
      </p>

      <p>
        For 1, see the section on <%= link_to 'sending an email invitation',
        '#sending-email-invitation' %>. For 2, your roommates will need to get
        the group identifier from you - it can be found on your
        <%= link_to 'profile', user_path(current_user) %> page. They'll enter
        this during the signup process.
      </p>

      <p>
        Once your roommates have joined, you can begin using the application.
        See the other sections for information regarding specific functionality.
      </p>
    </div>

    <div id="creating-chores">
      <h2>Creating chores</h2>
      <p>
        Apartmentalize provides the capability to create chores, which are then
        assigned to a user. Chores represent tasks which are to be completed
        regularly throughout an apartment - taking out the trash, cleaning the
        bathroom, etc.
      </p>
      <p>
        Chores can be created on the <%= link_to 'chores page', chores_path %>.
        There are 3 fields required when creating a new chore - title,
        description, and the user who the chore is initially assigned to. While
        chores can be edited, the idea is that they will be mostly static
        throughout their existence. The user selected when creating the chore
        will not remain constant - read more in the
        <%= link_to 'next section', '#cycling-chores' %>.
      </p>
    </div>

    <div id="cycling-chores">
      <h2>Cycling chores</h2>
      <p>
        As mentioned in the previous section, each chore is assigned to a user.
        While the title and description are expected to remian fairly constant,
        the user assigned to is not. All chores automatically cycle between
        users every Sunday at midnight. This behavior is currently not
        configurable, though there are plans for the future to allow more
        customization.
      </p>
    </div>

    <div id="creating-claims">
      <h2>Creating claims</h2>
      <p>
        One of the features of the site is the ability to track
        amounts of money that your roommates owe you for certain things -
        referred to hereafter as claims. Claims can be created on the
        <%= link_to 'main claims page', claims_path %>. The new claim form,
        displayed by default on the claims page, looks like this:

        <%= image_tag 'claim-form.png' %>

      </p>

      <p>
         There are several pieces of information to keep in mind when
         creating a claim:

        <ol>
          <li>
            There must be others users in the group for a claim to be created
          </li>
          <li>It is possible to create the same claim for multiple users at
            once - be aware that all other users in the group are selected
            by default</li>
          <li>Other users will be notified via the activity feed when a claim
            is created for them</li>
          <li>
            The 'split evenly' button includes you in the calculation. In the
            above photo, entering a claim amoutn of 60 and opting to split
            evenly will create two claims in the amount of 20, one for each
            roommate.
          </li>
        </ol>

        See the 'help' link at the bottom of the form for a walkthrough on
        creating a claim.
      </p>
    </div>

    <div id="marking-claim-paid">
      <h2>Marking claims as paid</h2>

      <p>
        Claims can either be paid or unpaid. Upon creation, a claim is marked
        as unpaid. An unpaid claim represents money
        that the other user has yet to pay. When that user pays you back
        for the amount of the claim, the claim should be marked as paid to
        indicate to both of you that the debt is complete. The user who owes
        the claim will receive a notification in their activity feed that the
        claim was marked as paid
      </p>

        <ol>
          <li>
            The main claims page, via the 'Mark paid' link
            <p><%= image_tag 'main-page-single-claim.png' %></p>
          </li>
          <li>
            The view page for an individual claim, accessible via the 'view'
            link in the above image.
            <p><%= image_tag 'claim-show-page.png' %></p>
          </li>
        </ol>

      </p>

      <p>
        Once a claim has been marked as paid, it cannot be changed back to
        unpaid. While this may cause some inconvenience, marking a claim as
        paid in theory represents the actual transfer of money between two
        people - if needed, the claim can simply be recreated.
      </p>

    </div>

    <div id="editing-claims">
      <h2>Editing claims</h2>

      <p>
        If an error is made when creating a claim (or you wish to update
        any properties), the claim can be edited via the 'Edit' button on the
        view page for a single claim. Note that the same restrictions apply -
        a title and valid amount are required.
      </p>

      <p>
        <%= image_tag 'edit-claim.png' %>
      </p>

      <p>
        The claim can also be deleted from the edit page. This action is
        permanent and will remove all traces of the claim from the site.
        Any activity feed items related to the deleted claim will be updated
        to reflect the deletion.
      </p>

      <p>
        After a claim has been marked as paid, the edit link will be disabled
        and the claim cannot be edited. This is to ensure that the claim
        reflects the state at the time it was paid.
      </p>

      <p>
        <%= image_tag 'disabled-button.png' %>
      </p>

    </div>

    <div id="commenting-on-claim">
      <h2>Commenting on a claim</h2>

      <p>
        It is possible to comment on individual claims. This functionality
        encourages discussion and allows any questions to be cleared up
        inline. Comments will be shown in chronological order, with the oldest
        comments displayed at the top. The content of the comment can be
        entered in the provided text box. The only restriction on comment content
        is that it must exist - attempting to create a blank comment will fail.
      </p>

      <p>
        <%= image_tag 'comment.png' %>
      </p>

      <p>
        When a comment is posted on a claim, the other user will be
        notified via the activity feed. Comments can also be edited or deleted,
        and can be posted after a claim has been marked as paid.
      </p>

    </div>

    <div id="searching-claims">
      <h2>Searching claims</h2>

      <p>
        Apartmentalize provides a robust search feature to look back through
        old claims. All searching occurs on the <%= link_to 'main claims page',
        claims_path %>. The search form, hidden by default, can be shown by
        clicking on the 'Search' button.
      </p>

      <p>
        <%= image_tag 'search-button.png' %>
      </p>

      <p>
        The form looks like this:
      </p>

      <p>
        <%= image_tag 'search-form.png' %>
      </p>

      <p>
        There are a few things to keep in mind when searching through claims:
        <ol>
          <li>
            Nothing is required to perform a search - a search with no
            parameters will simply return all claims related to you.
          </li>
          <li>
            Checking one button in a section does not preclude you from
            checking the other - for example, both 'Paid' and 'Unpaid' can be
            checked. That particular search would return both paid and unpaid
            claims, effectively not filtering on that particular criteria.
          </li>
          <li>
            You cannot search for claims that are not related to you - i.e.,
            claims that you either do not owe or are not owed.
          </li>
        </ol>
      </p>

      <p>
        Cilck the 'Help' link at the bottom of the search form for a walkthrough
        on searching claims.
      </p>

    </div>

    <div id="email-summaries">
      <h2>Email summaries</h2>

      <p>
        There are two types of email summaries you can receive:
      </p>

      <p>
        <ol>
          <li>
            <h5>Daily</h5>
            <p>Daily email summaries are sent out at the end of each day.
              They contain a list of claims you owe created on that day.
          </li>

          <li>
            <h5>Weekly</h5>
            <p>
              Weekly email summaries are sent out every Sunday. They contain
              balances between you and each roommate, the total balance between
              you and all roommates, and your chores for the week.
            </p>
          </li>
        </ol>
      </p>
      <p>
        You are NOT subscribed to these alerts by default. Subscription can be
        enabled by <%= link_to 'editing your account information',
        edit_user_registration_path(current_user) %>.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div id="sending-invitation">
    <h2>Sending an email invitation</h2>
    <p>
      To streamline the signup process, it is possible to send email
      invitation to people you would like to join your group on the site. This
      allows one user to efficiently complete setup. Invitations can be sent
      via your <%= link_to 'profile page', user_path(current_user) %>.
    </p>

    <p>
      <%= image_tag 'sending-invitation.png' %>
    </p>

    <p>
      You'll provide a name for the user (displayed on the site) and the email
      to send the invitation to. They will be able to edit both of these after
      they accept the invitation.
    </p>

    <p>
      You'll notice after the invitation is sent that the new account is visible
      to you. If the user does not accept the invitation within a week, their
      account will be deleted.
    </p>
  </div>

  <div id="activity-feed">
    <h2>Activity feed</h2>
    <p>
      The activity feed shows the 10 most recent selected activities relevant
      to you. It can be viewed on the <%= link_to 'home page', user_root_path %>.
      Activities which appears on the feed are:
    </p>

    <p>
      <ul>
        <li>A user creates a claim you owe</li>
        <li>A user marks a claim you owe as paid</li>
        <li>A user edits an existing claim</li>
        <li>A user comments on a claim related to you</li>
      </ul>
    </p>

    <p>The feed looks like:</p>
    <p>
      <%= image_tag 'activity-feed.png' %>
    </p>

    <p>
      Your own activity will not show up on your activity feed. It is currently
      not possible to configure the size of the feed or look back through items
      which are not the 10 most recent.
    </p>
  </div>

</div>

</div>
